      "title": "The Fixed Fifty Shekel Fine and Additional Payments for Rape",
      "display_title": "50 Shekel Fine",
      "timestamp": "00:41",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "How do we know the 50 shekel does not cover all payments including shame and depreciation",
          "display_title": "50 Shekel Coverage",
          "timestamp": "00:41"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Zeira's argument from comparing virgin and non-virgin victims",
          "display_title": "Virgin vs. Non-Virgin",
          "timestamp": "03:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "Abaye's counter-argument from the slave gored by an ox",
          "display_title": "Slave Market Precedent",
          "timestamp": "05:02"
        },
        {
          "title": "Abaye and Rava derive from verses that the 50 shekel is only for the act of intercourse itself",
          "display_title": "Verse Derivation",
          "timestamp": "06:02"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Determining Recipient and Basis for Shame and Depreciation Payments",
      "display_title": "Payment Recipients",
      "timestamp": "07:49",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Does shame and depreciation go to the woman or the father",
          "display_title": "Woman or Father",
          "timestamp": "07:49"
        },
        {
          "title": "All benefits from her youth go to the father from the verse about vow annulment",
          "display_title": "Youth Benefits",
          "timestamp": "09:10"
        },
        {
          "title": "Distinguishing between monetary rights, obligations about vows, and earnings",
          "display_title": "Types of Rights",
          "timestamp": "11:28"
        },
        {
          "title": "Father gets these payments because he has control over her status and shame",
          "display_title": "Father's Control",
          "timestamp": "13:06"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Calculating Damages Using the Slave Market Valuation",
      "display_title": "Slave Market Valuation",
      "timestamp": "15:55",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "How to determine damages: comparing prices of virgin vs. non-virgin slave women",
          "display_title": "Virgin vs. Non-Virgin Sl…",
          "timestamp": "15:55"
        },
        {
          "title": "Clarification: the slave buyer cares about virginity only when marrying her off to his slave",
          "display_title": "Slave Marriage Context",
          "timestamp": "16:14"
        },
        {
          "title": "Tosafot's difficulty with the slave market model not capturing actual losses to the woman",
          "display_title": "Tosafot's Critique",
          "timestamp": "18:12"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Dispute Between Rabbi Meir and the Sages on Sale and Fine Applicability",
      "display_title": "Meir vs. Sages",
      "timestamp": "22:45",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Meir: where there is sale there is no fine; where there is fine there is no sale",
          "display_title": "Meir's Position",
          "timestamp": "22:45"
        },
        {
          "title": "The sages: there can be both fine and sale for a ketana from three years and one day",
          "display_title": "Sages' Position",
          "timestamp": "23:55"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Meir learns from the verse 'to him she shall be for a wife' that only a naara applies",
          "display_title": "Verse Analysis",
          "timestamp": "25:16"
        },
        {
          "title": "The sages learn from the missing hei in naara that even a ketana is included",
          "display_title": "Missing Letter Hei",
          "timestamp": "26:06"
        },
        {
          "title": "Reish Lakish distinguishes: by motzi shem ra the hei indicates naara only, but context here is different",
          "display_title": "Motzi Shem Ra",
          "timestamp": "27:16"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Principle that Admission Does Not Obligate for Fines, Only for Monetary Payments",
      "display_title": "Admission & Fines",
      "timestamp": "46:33",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Someone admitting to seduction pays shame and depreciation but not the fine",
          "display_title": "Confession Rule",
          "timestamp": "46:33"
        },
        {
          "title": "General principle: fines require external witnesses and cannot be self-imposed",
          "display_title": "Fine vs. Compensation",
          "timestamp": "46:50"
        },
        {
          "title": "Application to theft: paying principal but not double and quadruple payments on admission",
          "display_title": "Theft Example",
          "timestamp": "47:36"
        },
        {
          "title": "The test: if payment sometimes exceeds actual damages, it is a fine not compensation",
          "display_title": "Exceeding Damages Test",
          "timestamp": "47:59"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Why the Mishna Uses Seduction Rather Than Rape in the Admission Example",
      "display_title": "Seduction vs. Rape",
      "timestamp": "48:14",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rape is obvious: he admits and must pay without spreading ill repute",
          "display_title": "Rape Case",
          "timestamp": "48:14"
        },
        {
          "title": "Seduction is instructive: he admits to spreading ill repute about the woman",
          "display_title": "Seduction Case",
          "timestamp": "48:29"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rebbi Shimon ben Yehuda: we do not believe him to accept payment for seduction",
          "display_title": "Rebbi Shimon",
          "timestamp": "48:39"
        },
        {
          "title": "Debate: do we protect family honor even if immediate parties consent to payment",
          "display_title": "Family Honor",
          "timestamp": "48:54"
        },
        {
          "title": "Tosafot: distinction between him admitting and the family suing him for admitted fact",
          "display_title": "Tosafot Distinction",
          "timestamp": "48:59"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Is Half Damages for a Non-Habitual Gorer Compensation or a Fine",
      "display_title": "Half Damages Debate",
      "timestamp": "50:36",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rav Pappa: half damages is compensation, the owner is barely negligent",
          "display_title": "Rav Pappa View",
          "timestamp": "50:36"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Huna: half damages is a fine to encourage caution, owner is not negligent",
          "display_title": "Rav Huna View",
          "timestamp": "50:53"
        },
        {
          "title": "The issue of how the sharing language applies if it is a fine not compensation",
          "display_title": "Sharing Language",
          "timestamp": "50:56"
        },
        {
          "title": "The carcass depreciation: owner of dead animal bears loss, indicating compensation logic",
          "display_title": "Carcass Depreciation",
          "timestamp": "51:57"
        },
        {
          "title": "The mishna on differences between tam and muad does not mention fine vs. compensation",
          "display_title": "Mishna Comparison",
          "timestamp": "54:01"
        }
      ]
    }
